{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657437","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657437"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:28:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:28:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19706"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19706"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.5,0,0.11,0.14,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12484"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96815"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12484","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12484"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19706"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79430"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"11576"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"11654"},{"type":"tags","id":"12509"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"29992"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33198"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96815"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EViral infections can damage host tissues through multiple mechanisms. Understanding these mechanisms is crucial for developing targeted therapeutic strategies.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how viruses most commonly cause tissue injury?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Host immune response","Inhibition of protein synthesis","Direct cell membrane disruption","Chromosomal integration","Metabolic depletion of host cells"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most common mechanism of tissue injury during viral infections is the \u003Cstrong\u003Ehost immune response\u003C/strong\u003E. While viruses can damage cells directly, most tissue injury occurs due to the inflammatory response and immune-mediated cell death, particularly through cytotoxic T cells, natural killer cells, and inflammatory cytokines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect cell membrane disruption\u003C/strong\u003E - While some viruses cause cell lysis during release, this is not the predominant mechanism of tissue injury for most viral infections\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetabolic depletion of host cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Although viruses utilize host cell resources, this rarely causes significant tissue damage\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChromosomal integration\u003C/strong\u003E - While some viruses integrate into host DNA, this process itself does not typically cause acute tissue injury\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of protein synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E - Though some viruses can shut down host protein synthesis, this is not the main mechanism of tissue damage\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding that immune responses cause most viral tissue injury explains why immunosuppressive treatments are sometimes used to reduce inflammation and tissue damage in severe viral infections.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Viruses can cause direct cell damage through lysis when new viral particles burst from infected cells.","Immune responses to viral infections, particularly cytotoxic T cells and inflammatory cytokines, can cause tissue injury.","Some viruses can trigger apoptosis in infected cells as part of their replication cycle."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; pagse 345-346."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79430"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19706"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79430"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T22:40:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T22:41:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12484"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96815"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4936"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immune System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4944"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Microbiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T15:37:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"14"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11576"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Mechanisms of viral injury","